 "modules": [
  {
   "title": "Module 1 · The Modulo Idea",
   "html": "<p>The symbol $a \\equiv b\\ (\\bmod\\ n)$ means <i>$a$ and $b$ leave the same remainder when divided by $n$</i>, equivalently, $n \\mid (a-b)$.</p><p>The <b>residues mod $n$</b> are $\\{0,1,2,\\ldots,n-1\\}$. Every integer is equivalent to exactly one of these.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Reduce $17$ mod $5$.",
     "a": "$17 = 3\\cdot 5 + 2$, so $17 \\equiv 2 \\pmod 5$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Reduce $-4$ mod $6$.",
     "a": "Add 6: $-4 + 6 = 2$, so $-4 \\equiv 2 \\pmod 6$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 2 · Addition, Subtraction, Multiplication mod $n$",
   "html": "<p>Reduce each operand mod $n$ first, then perform the operation, then reduce again.</p>$$(a+b)\\bmod n = ((a\\bmod n)+(b\\bmod n))\\bmod n$$$$(a\\cdot b)\\bmod n = ((a\\bmod n)\\cdot(b\\bmod n))\\bmod n$$",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "Compute $(23+18)\\bmod 7$.",
     "a": "$23\\equiv 2,\\ 18\\equiv 4 \\pmod 7$; $2+4=6$. So $(23+18)\\equiv 6\\pmod 7$."
    },
    {
     "q": "Compute $(9\\times 11)\\bmod 4$.",
     "a": "$9\\equiv 1,\\ 11\\equiv 3 \\pmod 4$; $1\\times 3=3$. Answer: $3$."
    }
   ]
  },
  {
   "title": "Module 3 · Applications in Daily Life",
   "html": "<p><b>Clocks</b> use mod 12; <b>days of the week</b> use mod 7; <b>calendar months</b> use mod 12. Any repeating cycle can be modelled with modular arithmetic.</p>",
   "examples": [
    {
     "q": "If today is Wednesday, what day will it be $100$ days from now?",
     "a": "Wednesday = day 3 (Sun=0). $3+100 = 103$; $103\\bmod 7 = 5$. Day 5 = Friday."
    },
    {
     "q": "The time now is 8 o'clock. What time will it be after 29 hours?",
     "a": "$(8+29)\\bmod 12 = 37 \\bmod 12 = 1$. Answer: 1 o'clock."
    }
   ]
  }
 ],
